flowRoot.flowPara: Consider a system of 4 physical qubits and the series of hamiltonians for them that are shown on the right. The terms in each hamiltonian all commute, and hence may be used as the stabilizer group for a quantum code. Underneath each hamiltonian is one possible choice of X and Z logical operators for the encoded qubit --- we say "one possible choice" because an equvalent choice can always be formed by multiplying either operator by a stabilizer.

We now consider what happens to our system when we change the first term in the hamiltonian from ZXZI to XIII. Note that the logical X operator, XZII, commutes with both of these operators. By contrast, the logical Z operator, ZIII, does not commute with XIII; however, the product of it with the first stablizer forms

the operator IXZI, which *does* commute with both XIII and ZXZI. Thus, we see that the subspace of the logical qubit is preserved by the transformation in the hamiltonian, as long as it is adiabatic. Furthermore, note that we may multiply the logical X operator, XZII, by the first of the new stabilizers, XIII, to form the operator IZII. Now in the new code --- which, again, has the same information as the old code, the logical X operator is IZII and the logical Z operator is IXZI. If we swap these operators, we get a new form for the logical qubit that is analgous to our original form. Hence, after the transformation, it is as if we had moved the information one step to the right and applied a Hadamard gate to it. We may repeat this procedure again to move the information a second time and apply another Hadamard gate to it.
